39· Final s was into Cicero's time a lightly sounded letter; it is frequently omitted in inscriptions, and does not make position when the following word begins with a consonant, even in the sixth foot of iambic senarius ι saluis sis, estis nunc, perdis me, etc. So also ain for ais-m, satin for satis-ue, etc. For this reason es, est unite freely with a pre ceding word ending in s; sariu's = sanus es, potitust = potitus est, unicust = unicus est, nactu's = nactus es, etc. Examples of these usages may be found 'rn abundance in any play.
